you can also denominate this in tao, since the ratio is the same. so:

the token is deeply discounted, because the liquidation price exceeds the price

the price is `tao in the pool divided by alpha in the pool`. if you sell 1 alpha in the pool, you should get back x amount of tao

the liquidation price is `tao in the pool divided by alpha held by users`. if the subnet were to be deregged, then for every alpha a user holds, they'd receive x amount of tao in return

I'll use sn42 as an example because the numbers are similar

price: 0.0033 tao
liquidation price: 0.0093 tao

let's say you have 10k alpha

if you were to swap your 10k alpha for tao through the pool, then you'd receive:
`10k * 0.0033 = 33 TAO`

if the subnet were to dereg, then you'd receive:
`10k * 0.0093 = 93 TAO`

so in a way, there is an incentive to buy the token, because if the subnet were to dereg, you'd get back 3x the amount of tao you started with. but the thing is, if people start mass buying to take advantage of this, you begin to push the price towards liquidation price, because the alpha token is getting more expensive as the pool adjusts the amount of tao and alpha in the pool with each buy

it's sort of the opposite when there is a premium i.e. price > liq. price. the market value of everyone's stake is overvalued instead of undervalued. the higher the ADR, the higher the likelihood of a bank run. e.g. everyone on paper appears to have 1000 TAO, but as soon as someone decides to sell, they drain the tao from the pool. and afterwards, now everyone's market value is 500 TAO. market value is closer to gdt (user's alpha stake / total alpha oustanding, multiplied by tao in the pool) and price is closer to liq. price

Absolute price seems pretty arbitrary, as it encodes a lot of history that is often irrelevant for the future. Just look at SN19, which has a price 11.6 mτ/α, emission 1.1% and *not even a discord channel*. Now let's suppose "the market" dumps their SN19 bags - price goes down only to 6.9 mτ/α, putting it still in the top 1/3 of subnets! So even if _nobody_ wants to hold SN19, it will still not come even close to deregistering, if price were the metric.

In other words, SN19 is immune from dereg just because its history made it so, by having ~17 kτ of ~22 kτ in its LP locked.

One could argue that price relative to lowest price, or, equivalently, αin:αheld, is a better metric. That would put SN19 up as the first candidate for dereg, cutting out 1.1% of emission, instead of SN86 with 0.09%. In general, it is a metric that does not depend on absolute price, and hence on emission, making it by definition more effective at redistributing emission than ranking subnets on price.

(sidenote: these conclusions don't all hold for the long term, when, post-halvings, the locked tao will slowly decrease)
